          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-800">Why Your Chair Matters</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-red-700">
            The average remote worker spends 6-10 hours per day sitting. A poor chair causes cumulative damage: lower back pain, neck strain, shoulder tension, and poor circulation. These are not minor inconveniences — chronic back pain is the leading cause of disability worldwide. A good ergonomic chair is not a luxury. It is a health investment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>What to Look For (The 6 Non-Negotiable Features)</h2>

        <h3>1. Adjustable Lumbar Support</h3>
        <p>This is the single most important feature. Lumbar support fills the gap between your lower back and the chair, maintaining the natural inward curve of your spine. Without it, you slouch — and slouching puts 40% more pressure on your spinal discs than sitting upright.</p>
        <p>Good lumbar support is <strong>adjustable in both height and depth</strong>. It should move up/down to match the curve of your specific spine, and in/out to provide the right amount of pressure. Fixed lumbar support (found on cheap chairs) is better than nothing, but adjustable is significantly better.</p>

        <h3>2. Seat Depth Adjustment</h3>
        <p>The seat pan should support your thighs without pressing against the back of your knees. The rule: when sitting all the way back, you should fit 2-3 fingers between the front edge of the seat and the back of your knees. If the seat is too deep, it cuts off circulation. Too shallow, and your thighs are not properly supported.</p>
        <p>A chair with seat depth adjustment (the seat slides forward and backward) lets you dial this in. This is especially important if you are shorter or taller than average.</p>

        <h3>3. Adjustable Armrests</h3>
        <p>Your armrests should support your forearms while typing without forcing your shoulders up. Look for at least 3-way adjustability: height, width, and pivot. Height adjustment is essential. Width and pivot are nice-to-haves that let you fine-tune the fit.</p>

        <h3>4. Tilt Mechanism with Tension Control</h3>
        <p>A good chair lets you recline slightly and lock the tilt at various angles. The tension control adjusts how much resistance you feel when leaning back. This matters more than you would think — shifting positions throughout the day is healthy, and a chair that locks you into one rigid position is actually worse for your back.</p>

        <h3>5. Breathable Back Material</h3>
        <p>Mesh backs are the standard for good reason: they are breathable and flexible. Foam and leather backs trap heat and get uncomfortable after a few hours. If your home office gets warm in the summer, a mesh back is a must.</p>

        <h3>6. Build Quality and Warranty</h3>
        <p>A good ergonomic chair should last 8-12 years. The warranty tells you what the manufacturer actually believes about their product. Herman Miller offers 12 years. Steelcase offers 12 years. Budget chairs often offer 1-2 years. The warranty length correlates strongly with how long the chair will actually last.</p>

        <h2>Best Ergonomic Chairs by Budget</h2>

        <h3>Under $200: Hbada Office Task Chair</h3>
        <p>Price: $120-150. The best chair you can buy for under $200. It has adjustable lumbar support, a mesh back, flip-up armrests, and a surprisingly comfortable seat. Not built to last a decade, but a solid 3-5 year chair. Ideal if you are just starting your home office journey.</p>

        <h3>$180-300: SIHOO M18 Ergonomic Office Chair</h3>
        <p>Price: $180-230. A clear step up. Full ergonomic adjustments including seat depth, lumbar height, headrest, and 3D armrests. The mesh back is well-ventilated. Frequently recommended on Reddit and YouTube as the best value ergonomic chair.</p>

        <h3>$500-800: Branch Ergonomic Chair Pro</h3>
        <p>Price: $530. A newer entrant that has quickly become popular. Seven points of adjustment, high-quality materials, and a clean modern design that does not look like a corporate office chair. 7-year warranty.</p>

        <h3>$1,000-1,500: Herman Miller Aeron (Size B)</h3>
        <p>Price: $1,100-1,400. The gold standard. The Aeron has been in production since 1994 and is the best-selling ergonomic chair of all time. The mesh suspension system (called Pellicle) distributes weight evenly and keeps you cool. Available in three sizes (A, B, C) to fit different body types. 12-year warranty. If you can afford it, buy it — it will outlast three cheaper chairs and likely save you from back problems.</p>

        <h3>$1,800+: Herman Miller Embody</h3>
        <p>Price: $1,800-2,200. Designed with input from 30+ physicians and PhDs. The backrest mimics a human spine with pixelated support points that adapt to your movement. If the Aeron is a precision tool, the Embody is a therapeutic device. Overkill for most people, but if you have existing back issues, it is worth every penny.</p>

        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 p-6 not-prose mt-10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-800">One Thing to Avoid</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-amber-700">
            Do not buy a "gaming chair." Despite their popularity, most gaming chairs are rebranded bucket seats from cars — designed to hold you in place during cornering, not to support your spine during 8 hours of typing. They typically lack proper lumbar support and force a C-shaped spine curve. Get an ergonomic office chair instead.
          </p>
